Example 2: Dynamic + Model Approach with Real Data

David D. Hofmann, Gabriele Cozzi, John Fieberg

2024-01-30

  • Purpose
  • Disclaimer
  • Preamble
  • Pre-Processing
  • Fitting Tentative Distributions
  • Generating Random Steps
  • Computing Covariates
  • Running the Model

Purpose

This example analysis serves to illustrate the application of the dynamic + model approach with real data collected on a spotted hyena (Crocuta crocuta) called Apollo. First, well do some slight pre-processing of the GPS data. Since missingness is really low in this dataset, well artificially increase it to a higher level. We will then apply the dynamic + model approach to estimate habitat and movement parameters.

Disclaimer

In this script, well utilize a set of custom functions that are stored in the Functions.R file. They are used to compute step-metrics, generate random-steps, and fit step distributions dynamically. Most of the functions can be replaced by much more generalized functions from the amt R-package. However, amts random_steps() function doesnt cope well with sampling random steps from distributions fit to different step-durations. Well therefore use of our custom code. If youd like to apply it to your own data, inspect the functions closels and verify that they suit your purposes.

Preamble

Lets start by preparing our R-Session and loading all necessary packages. We also load the custom functions stored in the Functions.R file.

# Set notation standards
options(scipen = 999)

# Clear R's brain
rm(list = ls())

# Load required packages
library(tidyverse)     # For data wrangling
library(sf)            # For plotting spatial features
library(lubridate)     # To handle dates and times
library(raster)        # For spatial data manipulation
library(amt)           # To fit step-length and turning-angle distributions
library(survival)      # To fit conditional logistic regression model
library(ggh4x)         # For nested ggplot facets

# Load custom functions
source("02_R-Scripts/Functions.R")

Pre-Processing

We start by loading the GPS data of a spotted hyena (Crocuta crocuta) and some covariate layers.

# Load hyena gps data and covariates
dat <- read_rds("03_Data/Hyena_GPS.rds") %>% subset(DOP < 10)
cov <- stack("03_Data/Hyena_Covariates.tif")

The hyena GPS data should have been collected every 2 hours, starting from 16:00 and until 04:00 oclock each day. There usually is also a fix collected at 10:00 oclock. Since hyenas are mainly nocturnal, were only going to focus on the nightly data and drop the 10:00 oclock fix. In very rare cases, two fixes fall on the same hour. Well drop such duplicates to avoid having step-durations that are less than 2 hours.

# Keep only fixes that were collected on the desired hour and drop potential
# duplicates
dat <- dat %>%
  mutate(timestamp = round_date(timestamp, "hour")) %>%
  subset(hour(timestamp) %in% c(16, 18, 20, 22, 0, 2, 4)) %>%
  distinct(id, timestamp, .keep_all = T)

# Assess the regular step-duration of our data
samp <- dat %>%
  computeDurations() %>%
  count(duration)
samp

If you take a look at the durations between subsequent fixes, youll find that most fixes are taken at 2-hourly intervals, with only few 4- or 6-hourly periods. This means that the data is pretty complete (i.e.there is relatively low missingness). To showcase the applicability of the dynamic+model approach well introduce a slightly higher level of missingness by removing a fraction of the collected GPS fixes.

# Incrase missingness a bit
dat_rarified <- dat %>%
  rarifyData(missingness = 0.15) %>%
  mutate(
      step_id     = 1:n()
    , step_number = 1:n()
  )

# Compare number of fixes
cbind(Original = nrow(dat), Rarified = nrow(dat_rarified))
##      Original Rarified
## [1,]     8169     6943

# Visualize covariates and the rarified track (normalization is only for

Fitting Tentative Distributions

Because we rarified the dataset, the time between consecutive datapoints is not always equal. Lets ensure the regular step-duration is still 2 hours.

# Assess the regular step-duration of our data
samp <- dat_rarified %>%
  computeDurations() %>%
  count(duration)
samp
## # A tibble: 15  2
##    duration       n
##    <drtn>     <int>
##  1    2 hours  4645
##  2    4 hours   837
##  3    6 hours   130
##  4    8 hours    26
##  5   12 hours   582
##  6   14 hours   500
##  7   16 hours   174
##  8   18 hours    31
##  9   20 hours     8
## 10   22 hours     5
## 11   24 hours     1
## 12  156 hours     1
## 13  286 hours     1
## 14 9158 hours     1
## 15   NA hours     1

As expected, the regular step-duration is 2 hours. However, we also observe that in a few cases the duration between two fixes can be as long as r max(samp$duration) hours. In regular iSSF, we would only consider bursts within which step-durations are somewhat comparable. Here, however, we are tolerant towards unequal step-durations, as well later account for differing step-durations in the model. Consequently, we would like to accommodate for differing durations by fitting tentative distributions for different step-durations. Here, allowing for steps of up to 6 hours appears sensible. Let us fit the associated step-length and turning angle distributions using the fitDists() function.

# Fit step-length and turning angle distributions to different durations
dists <- fitDists(dat_rarified
  , durations = c(2, 4, 6) # Return fitted distributions for durations 1-3
  , regular   = 2          # The regular step-duration is 2
  , dynamic   = T          # Fit distributions dynamically
  , resample  = F          # Don't resample the track
  , rarify    = F          # Don't increase missingness
)

# Show the fitted values
dists

##

## [1] 3309.642

You can see that we now have different gamma and von Mises parameters for steps from different durations. We can later use the so fitted distributions to generate random steps matching different step-durations.

Finally, we can use the computeSSF() function to generate 25 random steps for each valid step (a valid step has a step-length and a turning-angle associated). Note that we cna use the dynamically fitted distributions dists to match sampled random steps with the step-durations of observed steps by picking the dynamic+model approach. The function computeSSF() will also automatically drop any invalid steps or steps with a duration that occurs less than 5 times in the dataset. This is to prevent issues when including the step-duration in the iSSF model.

# Generate random steps
dat_rarified_ssf <- computeSSF(dat_rarified_metrics
  , n_rsteps = 25
  , dists    = dists
  , approach = "dynamic+model"
)
head(dat_rarified_ssf)

To be able to analyse our trajectory in an iSSF-framework, we need to generate random steps. Well use the amt package to generate these. However, unlike in traditional iSSFs, we will generate random steps using tentative distributions that are matched with the step-durations of observed steps. Lets start by converting our simulated dataframe into a track object (which is actually just a data.frame that contains all elements that amt requires to compute step-metrics).

Computing Covariates

We still need to compute all covariates that we want include our iSSF model. This includes spatial covariates at the end-point of each step, as well as step-metrics. We can use the function computeCovars for this.

# Compute covariates for all steps (the function will extract spatial covariates
# at the end of each step and also compute log_sl and cos_ta)
dat_rarified_covars <- computeCovars(dat_rarified_ssf
  , covars    = cov
  , extract   = "end"
)

Running the Model

We are now ready to estimate parameters using conditional logistic regression. This can be achieved using the clogit() function from the survival package. Alternatively, one can use the wrapper fit_clogit() from the amt package. Importantly, we will include interactions among the step-descriptors \(sl\), \(log(sl)\), and \(cos(ta)\) and the step-duration \(duration\).

# Ensure the step-duration enters as factor
dat_rarified_covars$duration <- as.factor(dat_rarified_covars$duration)

# Fit the model
mod <- clogit(data = dat_rarified_covars, formula = case ~
  + Water                     # Habitat-selection
  + DistanceToWater           # Habitat-selection
  + Trees                     # Habitat-selection
  + Water:duration            # Habitat x Step-Duration
  + DistanceToWater:duration  # Habitat x Step-Duration
  + Trees:duration            # Habitat x Step-Duration
  + sl                        # Movement Kernel
  + log_sl                    # Movement Kernel
  + cos_ta                    # Movement Kernel
  + sl:duration               # Movement x Step-Duration
  + log_sl:duration           # Movement x Step-Duration
  + cos_ta:duration           # Movement x Step-Duration
  + strata(step_id)
)

# Compute confidence intervals
ci <- confint(mod, level = 0.95)

# Put relevant results together
coefs <- summary(mod)$coefficients
coefs <- data.frame(
    Coefficient = rownames(coefs)
  , Estimate    = coefs[, "coef"]
  , SE          = coefs[, "se(coef)"]
  , Z           = coefs[, "z"]
  , LCI         = ci[, 1]
  , UCI         = ci[, 2]
)
